The `<gmp-place-autocomplete>` web component is the modern replacement for the legacy `Autocomplete` widget. There are two common mistakes to avoid: listening for `gmp-placeselect` (wrong) instead of `gmp-select` (correct), and trying to read `event.place` directly instead of calling `placePrediction.toPlace()` followed by `fetchFields()` [Source 1].

Here's a minimal working example:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
  <gmp-place-autocomplete id="pac"></gmp-place-autocomplete>
  <div id="result"></div>
  <gmp-map id="map" center="40.7128,-74.0060" zoom="12" map-id="DEMO_MAP_ID"></gmp-map>

  <script>
    async function init() {
      await google.maps.importLibrary("places");
      const { AdvancedMarkerElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("marker");

      const pac = document.getElementById("pac");
      const map = document.getElementById("map");
      let marker;

      pac.addEventListener("gmp-select", async ({ placePrediction }) => {
        // 1. Convert the prediction to a Place object
        const place = placePrediction.toPlace();

        // 2. Fetch only the fields you need (field mask controls billing)
        await place.fetchFields({
          fields: ["displayName", "formattedAddress", "location"],
        });

        // 3. Use the returned data
        document.getElementById("result").textContent =
          `${place.displayName} — ${place.formattedAddress}`;

        // 4. Update the marker
        if (marker) marker.map = null;
        marker = new AdvancedMarkerElement({
          map: map.innerMap,
          position: place.location,
          title: place.displayName,
        });
      });

      // Always handle errors
      pac.addEventListener("gmp-error", (e) => console.error(e));
    }
    init();
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

A few key things to know:

- **Session tokens are handled automatically.** The element internally manages `AutocompleteSessionToken`s, grouping keystrokes and the subsequent `fetchFields()` call into a single billed session. You don't need to create or pass tokens yourself [Source 3].
- **Field masks matter for billing.** Only list the fields you actually need in `fetchFields()` — you're only billed for what you request [Source 4].
- **Use `AdvancedMarkerElement`, not `google.maps.Marker`.** The legacy `Marker` class is deprecated; all new code should use `AdvancedMarkerElement`, which requires a `mapId` on the map [Source 5].
- **Error handling is important.** Listen for the `gmp-error` event to catch issues like network failures or invalid API keys.

**Sources:**
- [Places API (New)](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)
- [Deprecations and Migration Guide](https://developers.google.com/maps/deprecations)

## Loading the Maps JavaScript API in a React App

For new React/Next.js projects, the recommended approach is **`@googlemaps/js-api-loader` v2** or the **`@vis.gl/react-google-maps`** wrapper library. Here's a breakdown of both options [Source 1].

---

### Option 1: `@vis.gl/react-google-maps` (Recommended for React)

This is the preferred choice for new projects — it's team-maintained, StrictMode-safe, and built around `AdvancedMarkerElement` from day one [Source 1].

```tsx
// app/components/StoreMap.tsx
'use client'; // Required for Next.js App Router

import { APIProvider, Map, AdvancedMarker, Pin } from '@vis.gl/react-google-maps';

const center = { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 };

export default function StoreMap() {
  const apiKey = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY!;

  return (
    <APIProvider apiKey={apiKey} libraries={['marker']}>
      <Map
        defaultCenter={center}
        defaultZoom={12}
        mapId={process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_MAP_ID}
        style={{ width: '100%', height: 480 }}
        gestureHandling="cooperative"
      >
        <AdvancedMarker position={center} title="My Location">
          <Pin background="#EA4335" borderColor="#B31412" glyphColor="#fff" />
        </AdvancedMarker>
      </Map>
    </APIProvider>
  );
}
```

---

### Option 2: `@googlemaps/js-api-loader` v2 (Direct, no wrapper)

Use this if you need more control or want to avoid a wrapper dependency [Source 1, Source 3].

```tsx
// app/components/RawMap.tsx
'use client';

import { useEffect, useRef } from 'react';
import { setOptions, importLibrary } from '@googlemaps/js-api-loader';

// Call setOptions once at module scope — it's idempotent in v2
if (typeof window !== 'undefined') {
  setOptions({ key: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY!, v: 'weekly' });
}

export default function RawMap() {
  const containerRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);
  const mapRef = useRef<google.maps.Map | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    let cancelled = false;

    (async () => {
      const [{ Map }, { AdvancedMarkerElement }] = await Promise.all([
        importLibrary('maps') as Promise<google.maps.MapsLibrary>,
        importLibrary('marker') as Promise<google.maps.MarkerLibrary>,
      ]);
      if (cancelled || !containerRef.current) return;

      const map = new Map(containerRef.current, {
        center: { lat: 40.7128, lng: -74.0060 },
        zoom: 12,
        mapId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_MAP_ID,
      });
      mapRef.current = map;

      new AdvancedMarkerElement({ map, position: map.getCenter()!, title: 'NYC' });
    })();

    // Cleanup: cancel async work and drop map ref
    return () => {
      cancelled = true;
      mapRef.current = null;
    };
  }, []);

  return <div ref={containerRef} style={{ width: '100%', height: 480 }} />;
}
```

---

### Key things to watch out for

| Issue | Fix |
|---|---|
| `Loader must not be called again with different options` | Upgrade to v2 (`setOptions` + `importLibrary`), or use a single shared Loader instance [Source 2] |
| `ReferenceError: google is not defined` (SSR) | Mark the file `'use client'`, guard with `typeof window !== 'undefined'`, or use `next

The **Routes API** is Google Maps Platform's current, actively developed REST product for computing routes and travel-time matrices. The **Directions API** is its predecessor — still available as of 2026-04-21, but considered legacy and superseded [Source 1, Source 2].

Here's a practical breakdown of the key differences:

| Dimension | Directions API (Legacy) | Routes API (Current) |
|---|---|---|
| Status | Legacy — still available, no published sunset date | Actively developed, recommended for new integrations |
| Field masks | Not supported | Required — controls response shape **and** billing tier |
| Traffic models | Basic | `TRAFFIC_UNAWARE`, `TRAFFIC_AWARE`, `TRAFFIC_AWARE_OPTIMAL` |
| Travel modes | Standard | Adds `TWO_WHEELER` support |
| Toll/fuel awareness | No | Yes |
| Matrix computation | Distance Matrix API (separate) | `computeRouteMatrix` — unified in the same product |
| Billing | Legacy SKUs | Tiered Essentials/Pro/Enterprise SKUs ($5/$10/$15 per 1K at 0–100K volume) |

## Key practical implications

**Field masks save money.** With the Routes API, you declare exactly which fields you need via the `X-Goog-FieldMask` header. This determines both your response payload *and* which billing tier fires. If you only need distance and duration, you stay on the cheaper Essentials SKU ($5/1K) rather than accidentally paying for Enterprise fields [Source 2].

**Client-side routing** in the Maps JavaScript API still uses `DirectionsService` by name — that's the JS client companion and the name is preserved for historical reasons [Source 1].

## Routes API minimal example

```javascript
// REST call — server-side or from your backend
const response = await fetch(
  "https://routes.googleapis.com/directions/v2:computeRoutes",
  {
    method: "POST",
    headers: {
      "Content-Type": "application/json",
      "X-Goog-Api-Key": "YOUR_API_KEY",
      // Only request what you need — this keeps you on the Essentials SKU
      "X-Goog-FieldMask": "routes.duration,routes.distanceMeters,routes.polyline.encodedPolyline",
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      origin: { location: { latLng: { latitude: 37.419734, longitude: -122.0827784 } } },
      destination: { location: { latLng: { latitude: 37.41767, longitude: -122.079595 } } },
      travelMode: "DRIVE",
      routingPreference: "TRAFFIC_AWARE",
    }),
  }
);

if (!response.ok) {
  throw new Error(`Routes API error: ${response.status} ${response.statusText}`);
}

const data = await response.json();
const route = data.routes[0];
console.log(`Distance: ${route.distanceMeters}m`);
console.log(`Duration: ${route.duration}`);
```

## Bottom line

Use the **Routes API for all new integrations**. No sunset date has been announced for the Directions API, but Google is directing investment into Routes — field masks, better traffic models, two-wheeler routing, and toll/fuel awareness are Routes-only features [Source 1].

**Sources:**
- [Routes API Overview](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/routes/overview)
- [Google Maps Platform Billing and Pricing](https://developers.google.com/maps/billing-and-pricing/pricing)

## OVER_QUERY_LIMIT Error

This error means you've exceeded either your queries-per-second (QPS) or daily quota limit for the API [Source 1]. It's a quota issue, not an API key restriction problem — those are separate failure modes [Source 4].

There are three ways to resolve it:

1. **Implement exponential backoff** — retry failed requests with increasing delays rather than hammering the API repeatedly
2. **Batch requests** where the API supports it
3. **Check and increase your quota** — Cloud Console → APIs & Services → Quotas. If you're consistently hitting limits, request a quota increase

If you've set a daily quota cap intentionally, you'll see this error with the message `"You have exceeded your daily request quota for this API."` — that's the quota cap working as designed [Source 3].

```javascript
async function geocodeWithRetry(address, retries = 3) {
  for (let i = 0; i < retries; i++) {
    try {
      const result = await geocoder.geocode({ address });
      return result;
    } catch (error) {
      if (error.code === "OVER_QUERY_LIMIT" && i < retries - 1) {
        // Exponential backoff: 1s, 2s, 4s...
        await new Promise(resolve =>
          setTimeout(resolve, Math.pow(2, i) * 1000)
        );
        continue;
      }
      throw error; // Re-throw if out of retries or different error
    }
  }
}
```

One important distinction: **budget alerts do NOT stop traffic** — only quota caps do [Source 3]. If you're getting `OVER_QUERY_LIMIT` unexpectedly, verify you haven't set a hard quota cap in Cloud Console → APIs & Services → Google Maps Platform → [API] → Quotas & System Limits.

**Sources:**
- [Common Errors and Troubleshooting](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/error-messages)
- [API Key Auth and Restrictions](https://developers.google.com/maps/api-security-best-practices)
- [Google Maps Platform Billing and Pricing](https://developers.google.com/maps/billing-and-pricing/pricing)

Use the **Places API (New)** — specifically the `<gmp-place-autocomplete>` web component. The legacy Places API is now in legacy status and **cannot be enabled for new Google Cloud projects** [Source 2]. If you're starting a new project or migrating, the modern surface is your only real option.

The three migration changes that matter most for autocomplete [Sources 1, 4]:

| Legacy | Current |
|---|---|
| `new google.maps.places.Autocomplete(input, ...)` | `<gmp-place-autocomplete>` element |
| `autocomplete.addListener("place_changed", ...)` | `element.addEventListener("gmp-select", ...)` |
| `autocomplete.getPlace()` | `placePrediction.toPlace()` from the `gmp-select` event payload |
| `AutocompleteService.getPlacePredictions()` | `AutocompleteSuggestion.fetchAutocompleteSuggestions()` (or just use the element) |

The new element also handles **session tokens automatically** — in the legacy flow you had to manage `AutocompleteSessionToken` yourself. Session tokens are the single biggest autocomplete cost optimization (they bundle keystrokes + the subsequent Place Details call into one billed session), so getting this for free is a meaningful improvement [Source 4].

Here's a minimal working example with the new element:

```javascript
// Load the places library
const { PlaceAutocompleteElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");

// Or use the HTML web component directly:
// <gmp-place-autocomplete></gmp-place-autocomplete>

const autocompleteElement = document.querySelector("gmp-place-autocomplete");

autocompleteElement.addEventListener("gmp-select", async (event) => {
  const placePrediction = event.placePrediction;

  // Convert prediction to a Place and fetch fields you need
  const place = placePrediction.toPlace();
  await place.fetchFields({
    fields: ["displayName", "formattedAddress", "location"],
  });

  console.log(place.displayName);
  console.log(place.formattedAddress);
  console.log(place.location.lat(), place.location.lng());
});
```

A couple of things worth knowing:
- **Field masks are required** on the `fetchFields()` call — only fields you name are returned and billed [Source 2].
- Fine-grained styling (highlight color, per-row icons) is limited; the documented CSS parts are `::part(input)`, `::part(prediction-list)`, and `::part(prediction-item)` [Source 4].

**Sources:**
- [Places API (New)](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)
- [Deprecations and Migration Guide](https://developers.google.com/maps/deprecations)
